    <name>
				<text>14.4.1b Length of curve 2</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Find the length of the curve \(y = x^2\) between \(x = {@xmin@}\) and \(x = {@xmax@}\).</p>
<p>Given \(y=x^2\) then \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}=2x\). Use this result and apply the formula in the first Key Point to obtain the integral required:</p>
<p>\(\displaystyle{\int_{{@xmin@}}^{{@xmax@}}}\) [[input:ans1]] \(\mathrm{d}x\)</p>
<p>[[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>
<p>Make the substitution \(x=\dfrac{1}{2}\sinh u\), giving \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}x}{\mathrm{d}u}=\dfrac{1}{2}\cosh u\), to obtain an integral in terms of \(u\):</p>
<p>\(\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{\sinh^{-1} {@2*xmax@}}}\) [[input:ans2]] \(\mathrm{d}u\)</p>
<p>[[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</p>
<p>Use the hyperbolic identity \(\cosh^2 u - \sinh^2 u \equiv 1\) to eliminate \(\sinh^2 u\):</p>
<p>\(\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{\sinh^{-1} {@2*xmax@}}}\) [[input:ans3]] \(\mathrm{d}u\)</p>
<p>[[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]</p>
<p>Use the hyperbolic identity \(\cosh^2 u = \frac{1}{2}(\cosh 2u +1)\) to rewrite the integrand in terms of \(\cosh 2u\): </p>
<p>\(\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{\sinh^{-1} {@2*xmax@}}}\) [[input:ans4]] \(\mathrm{d}u\)</p>
<p>[[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]</p>
<p>Finally, perform the integration to find the required length, giving your answer to <b>2 decimal places</b>.</p>
<p>[[input:ans5]]</p>
<p>[[validation:ans5]] [[feedback:prt5]]</p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p>The formula in the Key Point tells us that, given a curve with equation \(y=f(x)\), the length of the curve between the points where \(x=a\) and \(x=b\) is given by the formula \[\int_a^b \sqrt{1+\left(\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\right)^2} \: \mathrm{d}x\]</p>
<p>Therefore, our required integral is \[\int_{0}^{\sinh^{-1} {@2*xmax@}} \sqrt{1+4 x^2} \: \mathrm{d}x\]</p>
<p>Using the substitution \(x=\frac{1}{2}\sinh u\), we calculate that the upper limit is \(u=\sinh^{-1}(2\cdot {@xmax@})=\sinh^{-1}({@2*xmax@})\), and the lower limit is \(u=0.\)</p>
<p>Therefore, the integral becomes \[\int_{0}^{\sinh^{-1} {@2*xmax@}} \sqrt{1+\sinh^2 u}\frac{1}{2}\cosh u \: \mathrm{d}u\]</p>
<p>Using the hyperbolic identity \(\cosh^2 u - \sinh^2 u \equiv 1\), we eliminate \(\sinh^2 u\), to obtain \[\frac{1}{2}\int_{0}^{\sinh^{-1} {@2*xmax@}}\cosh^2 u \: \mathrm{d}u\]</p>
<p>Using the hyperbolic identity \(\cosh^2 u = \frac{1}{2}(\cosh 2u +1)\), the integrand can be written as \[\frac{1}{4}\int_{0}^{\sinh^{-1} {@2*xmax@}} (\cosh 2u + 1) \: \mathrm{d}u\]</p>
<p>Now we can perform the integration:</p>
<p> \( \begin{aligned} \frac{1}{4} \int_{0}^{\sinh^{-1} {@2*xmax@}} (\cosh 2u + 1) \: \mathrm{d}u &amp; = \frac{1}{4} \left[ \frac{\sinh 2 u}{2} + u \right]_{0}^{\sinh^{-1} {@2*xmax@}}
    \\ &amp; = \frac{1}{4} \left(\left( \frac{\sinh(2\cdot \sinh^{-1}({@2*xmax@}))}{2}+\sinh^{-1}({@2*xmax@}) \right)-\left( \frac{\sinh(2\cdot 0)}{2}+0\right)\right) \\ &amp; = {@ta5@} \end{aligned} \)</p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
